"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776110","Department for Education","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency collects and publishes data on the number of individuals enrolled in and entering higher education courses. This includes information on the area each student lived in before they entered university, which is used as a proxy for disadvantage.</p><p>This growth in participation is seen in the latest disadvantaged entry rates published by the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service, which show that in 2016 young people from the most disadvantaged areas were 43% more likely to enter full-time higher education than they were in 2009 (19.5%, up from 13.6%).</p><p>In 2011/12, 41,405 full-time English-domiciled undergraduate students from low participation areas (defined as being in the lowest quintile of the POLAR3 classification) entered English higher education institutions. The equivalent figure for 2015/16 was 44,285, representing a 7% increase in full-time undergraduate entrants from low participation areas between 2011/12 and 2015/16.</p><p>In 2011/12, 30,845 part-time English-domiciled undergraduate students from low participation areas entered English higher education institutions. The equivalent figure for 2015/16 was 16,330, representing a 47% decrease in part-time undergraduate entrants from low participation areas between 2011/12 and 2015/16.</p><p>Information for all years since 2008/09 could only be provided at disproportionate cost to the department. Information for the years 2011/12 and 2015/16 has been provided, in line with PQ 109021.</p><p>More detailed counts of students (including numbers of mature students) can be found in the table provided.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","109021","2017-11-14T11:45:26.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776110/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776110/answer","109021, 109016 excel attachment.xlsx","English domiciled entrants registered at HEIs","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776110/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-23","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) mature and (b) part-time students from disadvantaged backgrounds have entered higher education in England in each year since 2008-09.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","109016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776111","Department for Education","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency collects and publishes data on the number of individuals enrolled in and entering higher education courses. This includes information on the area each student lived in before they entered university, which is used as a proxy for disadvantage.</p><p>This growth in participation is seen in the latest disadvantaged entry rates published by the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service, which show that in 2016 young people from the most disadvantaged areas were 43% more likely to enter full-time higher education than they were in 2009 (19.5%, up from 13.6%).</p><p>In 2011/12, 41,405 full-time English-domiciled undergraduate students from low participation areas (defined as being in the lowest quintile of the POLAR3 classification) entered English higher education institutions. The equivalent figure for 2015/16 was 44,285, representing a 7% increase in full-time undergraduate entrants from low participation areas between 2011/12 and 2015/16.</p><p>In 2011/12, 30,845 part-time English-domiciled undergraduate students from low participation areas entered English higher education institutions. The equivalent figure for 2015/16 was 16,330, representing a 47% decrease in part-time undergraduate entrants from low participation areas between 2011/12 and 2015/16.</p><p>Information for all years since 2008/09 could only be provided at disproportionate cost to the department. Information for the years 2011/12 and 2015/16 has been provided, in line with PQ 109021.</p><p>More detailed counts of students (including numbers of mature students) can be found in the table provided.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","109016","2017-11-14T11:45:26.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776111/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776111/answer","109021, 109016 excel attachment.xlsx","English domiciled entrants registered at HEIs","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776111/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-23","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many England-domiciled (a) full-time and (b) part-time undergraduate students entered higher education institutions in England from disadvantaged areas to study in (i) 2011-12 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","109021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776112","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-31","<p>The UK will continue to have all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings, up until the point we leave the EU. Where transposition deadlines fall after the UK has left the EU, the outcome will depend on UK-EU negotiations.</p><p>We want to be the first generation to leave the environment of England in a better state than we inherited it. We remain committed to making the most of our resources, to reducing waste and to increasing reuse and recycling.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-31T14:59:58.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776112/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776112/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-23","Waste Management: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether new EU waste and recycling legislation being negotiated at EU level will apply in the UK given the deadline for transposing that legislation falling after the UK plans to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","109018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776113","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-30","<p><strong> </strong>The Government is considering the Crossrail 2 Strategic Outline Business Case, submitted by Transport for London, to determine whether the proposed scheme delivers value for money to the UK taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The approach is consistent with the HM Treasury Green Book guidance and focusses on the use of cost benefit (welfare) analysis to determine value for money. This captures the expected economic, environmental and social impacts of the scheme on the UK.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-30T16:57:57.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776113/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776113/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-23","Crossrail 2 Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the potential contribution of Crossrail 2 to national economic growth.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","109017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776114","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Police Counter-Terrorism Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU) refers content that they assess as contravening UK terrorism legislation and companies terms and conditions to Communications Service Providers (CSPs). This includes content of proscribed UK organisations such as National Action and its aliases.</p><p> </p><p>If CSPs agree that it breaches their terms and conditions they remove it voluntarily. Following the proscription of National Action in December 2016, HMG requested CSPs to remove and restrict access to National Action content.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","109107","2017-11-23T13:24:52.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776114/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-23","Proscribed Organisations: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many websites for (a) Scottish Dawn, (b) NS131 and (c) National Action have been removed since those organisations were proscribed.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","109106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776115","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The Police Counter-Terrorism Internet Referral Unit (CTIRU) refers content that they assess as contravening UK terrorism legislation and companies terms and conditions to Communications Service Providers (CSPs). This includes content of proscribed UK organisations such as National Action and its aliases.</p><p> </p><p>If CSPs agree that it breaches their terms and conditions they remove it voluntarily. Following the proscription of National Action in December 2016, HMG requested CSPs to remove and restrict access to National Action content.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace","109106","2017-11-23T13:24:52.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776115/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776115/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-23","Proscribed Organisations: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for how long websites for (a) Scottish Dawn, (b) NS131 and (c) National Action remained live after those organisations were proscribed.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","109107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776116","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-26","<p>Data from Thinkbroadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/weaver-vale,E14001024) and the Department's own models indicate that, of the 40,400 premises in Weaver Vale, 2.4% or approximately 975 premises do not have access to what the Department determines to be 'high speed' broadband (more than 10Mbits/second). We do not hold this figure broken down between residential, commercial and industrial premises.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-26T11:40:07.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776116/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776116/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-23","Broadband: Weaver Vale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment her Department has made of the number and proportion of households in Weaver Vale constituency which do not have access to high-speed broadband.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","108973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776117","Department for Education","false","2017-10-26","<p>The Government will offer Mayoral Combined Authorities the oppotunity to shape their Adult Education Budgets (AEBs) in 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with Mayoral Combined Authorities to help them prepare for devolution of the AEB in 2019/20, including the proposed 2018/19 transitional year.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayoral Combined Authorities have been consulted with regards to the interim options available and the details of these will be communicated within the next few weeks.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-26T15:54:27.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776117/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776117/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-23","Adult Education: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish detailed guidance relating to the operational differences between the influencing role and the delegated model in relation to the interim options provided to the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority on responsibility for the 2018-19 adult skills budget; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","108974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776118","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>All existing claimants will be offered a support for mortgage interest loan paid at the same rate that is currently available as part of their benefit entitlement. The new loans-based support for mortgage interest will only affect claimants’ financial situation on the sale or transfer of the property, when the loan will be recovered from any available equity.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not propose to undertake formal evaluation of this change. However, we are committed to monitoring the impacts of our policies and will use evidence from a number of sources to assess the impact on an on-going basis. This will include the updated data that is available to DWP on a quarterly basis, survey data (such as the Family Resources Survey) and feedback from stakeholder groups, including via our regular liaison with UK Finance, to assess whether there are unintended consequences for particular groups.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-30T14:32:06.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776118/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776118/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-23","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of his decision to end the Support for Mortgage Interest allowance on the financial situation of those currently in receipt of that allowance.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","109130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776119","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>Transitional provisions are in the Social Security Loans for Mortgage Interest Regulations 2017 to enable claimants who are receiving support for mortgage interest as part of their benefit on 5 April 2018 to have a temporary period in which they can still receive SMI as a benefit. This will allow the SMI benefit payments to continue should there be delays in the operational activity to migrate existing claimants to the loans scheme. This will enable the first loan payment to be made shortly after 6 April if that date falls during the claimant’s benefit week (in the case of a claimant of Income Support, income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance, income-related Employment and Support Allowance and State Pension Credit) or assessment period (in the case of a Universal Credit claimant) so that there is no gap in payment between the last SMI benefit award and the first loan payment.</p><p> </p><p>Where an existing claimant lacks mental capacity to make decisions about entering into the loan agreement, the regulations provide for support for mortgage interest as a benefit to continue until a final determination is made as to whether to appoint an appropriate person to act on the claimant’s behalf (such as a Financial Deputy) in respect of the loan agreement.</p><p> </p><p>Transitional provisions are also included to ease the transition from Income Support, income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance and income-related Employment and Support Allowance to universal credit. Where a claimant who has served the qualifying period in respect of support for mortgage interest before moving on to universal credit, the claimant will not have to serve the qualifying period again (subject to satisfying certain conditions).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-30T15:09:38.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776119/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/776119/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-23","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will introduce transitional measures for claimants in receipt of support for mortgage interest when his Department ends the Support for Mortgage Interest allowance.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","109131"
